SIMPLE: sweep
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sweep
<hw>Sweep</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swept</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sweeping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>swepen</ets>; akin to
AS. <ets>sw⟦amac⟧pan</ets>. See <er>Swoop</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass a broom across (a surface) so as to remove
loose dirt, dust, etc.; to brush, or rub over, with a broom for the
purpose of cleaning; <as>as, to <ex>sweep</ex> a floor, the street, or a
chimney</as>. Used also figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>sweep</qex> it with the besom of destruction.</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. xiv. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drive or carry along or off with a broom or a
brush, or as if with a broom; to remove by, or as if by, brushing;
<as>as, to <ex>sweep</ex> dirt from a floor; the wind <ex>sweeps</ex>
the snow from the hills; a freshet <ex>sweeps</ex> away a dam, timber,
or rubbish; a pestilence <ex>sweeps</ex> off multitudes.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hail shall <qex>sweep</qex> away the refuge of lies.</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. xxviii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have already <qex>swept</qex> the stakes.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To brush against or over; to rub lightly
along.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their long descending train,⟦br⟧
With rubies edged and sapphires, <qex>swept</qex> the plain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To carry with a long, swinging, or dragging motion;
hence, to carry in a stately or proud fashion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And like a peacock <qex>sweep</qex> along his tail.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To strike with a long stroke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wake into voice each silent string,⟦br⟧
And <qex>sweep</qex> the sounding lyre.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To draw or drag something over;
<as>as, to <ex>sweep</ex> the bottom of a river with a
net</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To pass over, or traverse, with the eye or with an
instrument of observation; <as>as, to <ex>sweep</ex> the heavens with a
telescope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To sweep a mold</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
sweep up a mold</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Founding)</fld>, <cd>to form the
sand into a mold by a templet, instead of compressing it around the
pattern.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sweep</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sweep
<hw>Sweep</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To clean
rooms, yards, etc., or to clear away dust, dirt, litter, etc., with a
broom, brush, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To brush swiftly over the surface of anything; to
pass with switness and force, as if brushing the surface of anything; to
move in a stately manner; <as>as, the wind <ex>sweeps</ex> across the
plain; a woman <ex>sweeps</ex> through a drawing-room.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pass over anything comprehensively; to range
through with rapidity; <as>as, his eye <ex>sweeps</ex> through
space</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sweep</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sweep
<hw>Sweep</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
sweeping.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The compass or range of a stroke; <as>as, a long
<ex>sweep</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The compass of any turning body or of any motion;
<as>as, the <ex>sweep</ex> of a door; the <ex>sweep</ex> of the
eye</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The compass of anything flowing or brushing; <as>as,
the flood carried away everything within its
<ex>sweep</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Violent and general destruction; <as>as, the
<ex>sweep</ex> of an epidemic disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Direction and extent of any motion not rectilinear;
<as>as, the <ex>sweep</ex> of a compass</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Direction or departure of a curve, a road, an arch,
or the like, away from a rectilinear line.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The road which makes a small <qex>sweep</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>One who sweeps; a sweeper; specifically, a chimney
sweeper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>A movable templet for making
molds, in loam molding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The mold of a ship
when she begins to curve in at the rungheads; any part of a ship shaped
in a segment of a circle.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A large oar used in
small vessels, partly to propel them and partly to steer them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Refining)</fld> <def>The almond furnace.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>A long pole, or piece of timber, moved on a
horizontal fulcrum fixed to a tall post and used to raise and lower a
bucket in a well for drawing water.</def> <altsp>[Variously written
<asp>swape</asp>, <asp>sweep</asp>, <asp>swepe</asp>, and
<asp>swipe</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>In the game of casino, a
pairing or combining of all the cards on the board, and so removing them
all; in whist, the winning of all the tricks (thirteen) in a hand; a
slam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The sweeping of workshops where
precious metals are worked, containing filings, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sweep net</b></col>, <cd>a net for drawing over a large
compass.</cd> -- <col><b>Sweep of the tiller</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a circular frame on which the tiller
traverses.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sweepage</ent>⟦br⟧
